# RESEARCH SUMMARY

## Area 1: Debug why `__del__` objects end up in `gc.garbage`

**File:** `Python/gc.c` (not `Modules/gcmodule.c` in this CPython version)

### Key functions

**`has_legacy_finalizer(op)`** — lines 678–682
```c
/* Return true if object has a pre-PEP 442 finalization method. */
static int
has_legacy_finalizer(PyObject *op)
{
    return Py_TYPE(op)->tp_del != NULL;
}
```

**`move_legacy_finalizers(unreachable, finalizers)`** — lines 690–713  
Called at line **1537** in `gc_collect_main()`, *before any finalizers run*. Walks the `unreachable` list; any object with `tp_del != NULL` is moved to the `finalizers` list and `NEXT_MASK_UNREACHABLE` is stripped.

**`handle_legacy_finalizers(tstate, gcstate, finalizers, old)`** — lines 1018–1039  
Called at line **1605** in `gc_collect_main()`, *after* `tp_finalize` calls, weakref callbacks, and `tp_clear`. The exact C condition that causes an object to land in `gc.garbage`:
```c
if ((gcstate->debug & _PyGC_DEBUG_SAVEALL) || has_legacy_finalizer(op)) {
    if (PyList_Append(gcstate->garbage, op) < 0) { ... }
}
```
Line 1030. After appending, `gc_list_merge(finalizers, old)` at line 1038 puts them into the old generation forever — they are never freed.

**`gc_list_merge(from, to)`** — lines 275–293  
O(1) doubly-linked list append: splices `from` onto `to`'s tail, then re-initialises `from` as empty.

### `tp_finalize` vs `tp_del`

| | `tp_finalize` (PEP 442, Python 3.4+) | `tp_del` (legacy) |
|---|---|---|
| Detected at | `finalize_garbage()` line 1065: `!_PyGC_FINALIZED(op) && Py_TYPE(op)->tp_finalize != NULL` | `has_legacy_finalizer()` line 682 |
| When executed | Line 1560 — **during** collection, on the `unreachable` list | **Never** during collection |
| Fate | Object may be resurrected, then freed | Moved to `finalizers`; appended to `gc.garbage` |
| Python `__del__` maps to | `tp_finalize` (post-3.4 classes) | `tp_del` (old-style C extension types) |

### Collection cycle call order (`gc_collect_main`, line 1422)

| Line | Call |
|------|------|
| 1509 | `deduce_unreachable(young, &unreachable)` |
| 1537 | `move_legacy_finalizers(&unreachable, &finalizers)` — extracts `tp_del` objects |
| 1542 | `move_legacy_finalizer_reachable(&finalizers)` |
| 1555 | `handle_weakref_callbacks(&unreachable, old)` |
| 1560 | `finalize_garbage(tstate, &unreachable)` — calls `tp_finalize` |
| 1566 | `handle_resurrected_objects(...)` |
| 1574 | `clear_weakrefs(&final_unreachable)` |
| 1581 | `delete_garbage(...)` — calls `tp_clear` |
| 1605 | `handle_legacy_finalizers(...)` — **appends to gc.garbage** |

**PEP 442 change:** Before Python 3.4, objects with `__del__` in a cycle were unconditionally uncollectable. PEP 442 introduced `tp_finalize` so that objects with `__del__` defined in Python (not C `tp_del`) can now be finalized and collected. Only objects whose *C type* sets `tp_del` still land in `gc.garbage`.

