## Design notes

**Why three separate locations?**

| File | What goes there |
|---|---|
| `Objects/dictobject.c` | The `/*[clinic input]*/` annotation block and the `_impl` function body |
| `Objects/clinic/dictobject.c.h` | The clinic-generated docstring, `#define` macro, forward declaration, and critical-section wrapper — normally produced by `python Tools/clinic/clinic.py Objects/dictobject.c`, but shown here explicitly |
| `mapp_methods[]` in dictobject.c | The `DICT_POP_LAST_METHODDEF` macro that exposes the method on `dict` |

**Split-table handling** — `_PyDict_HasSplitTable(self)` is true when `ma_values != NULL`. Split tables have their values stored separately in `ma_values->values[]` rather than inline with the keys. Before we can do a reverse scan over `dk_entries[]` and null out the value slot, we must call `dictresize(..., 1)` to collapse the split table into a combined one, exactly as `popitem()` does.

**Why allocate the tuple before the emptiness check?** — The `PyTuple_New(2)` call can trigger GC, which can run finalizers, which can mutate the dict (emptying it). If we checked `ma_used == 0` first and the dict later became empty during allocation, we'd find a live entry in the tuple but a `ma_used` of 0 afterward, breaking invariants. Allocating first and then checking (and discarding the tuple on empty) is the established CPython idiom.

**`STORE_KEYS_NENTRIES(self->ma_keys, i)`** — `i` is the index of the entry we just removed. Setting `dk_nentries` to `i` (not `i-1`) reclaims all tail space up to and including the removed entry. This is correct because the removed slot is now NULL and will never be re-used as a valid entry; subsequent insertions start from `dk_nentries` again.

**No `dk_usable++`** — because `dictkeys_set_index(..., DKIX_DUMMY)` leaves a tombstone in the hash index array. A dummy slot cannot be reclaimed by incrementing `dk_usable`; it can only be reclaimed by a future `dictresize`.

